///
/// "How to use"
@Node "use" "How to use GoScreen"

GoScreen is started from Shell (CLI). The options are case sensetive.

@{u}@{b}Shell (CLI) usage:@{uu}@{ub}

The following commandline options are supported:
------------------------------------------------

TEMPLATE:

	MODEID<DisplayID>,NAME<screenname>,PUBLIC=/N,FONT<font> /N

 MODEID (required)
  Give here a hexadecimal number that represents the display and it's resolution, colors.
  You can use the program Scout, available at Aminet, to see all MODEID's of the Amiga.
  When you start Scout, doubleclick in it's main window on the "ScreenModes" gadget, a window
  appears with screenmodes and it's corresponding ModeID. Now, take a number
  to put behind the option MODEID. 

 NAME (required)
  Give behind this option the name of the screen. Put quotes arround name that contains spaces.

 PUBLIC=
  A number here gives the time how long our screen the default public screen is. Normaly, the
  Workbench is the default public screen. PUBLIC=400 means 8 seconds, when a program starts within
  these 8 seconds, it appears on our screen. Works only with programs that are not configured for
  an own screen and not forced on Workbench screen. GoScreen closes the screen when the programs
  are gone. The original default public screen is given back after the 8 seconds. If the original
  default public screen was closed, the Workbench becomes default public. Default PUBLIC is 0.

 FONT
  Choose a font and it's size for the screen. Defaults Workbench alike.


Shell (CLI) Examples:
---------------------

@{fg shine}-1-@{fg text}

@{fg fill}MODEID 50021000 NAME AmigaWriter@{fg text}

Opens the screen named "AmigaWriter" with the in MODEID coresponding screenmode.
No option PUBLIC was given, because in the AmigaWriter program you can choose
the screen. Start now AmigaWriter and it opens on this screen.

@{fg shine}-2-@{fg text}

@{fg fill}MODEID $50021000 NAME "StormC Screen" PUBLIC=800 FONT helvetica.font 15@{fg text}

Opens the screen named "StormC Screen" with the in MODEID coresponding screenmode.
PUBLIC=800 means for 16 seconds becomes "StormC Screen" default public.
The font "helvetica.font", size 15 is used as screen font.
Start now StormC and it opens on this screen.
Note, you can put character "$" before the ModeID number or not, makes no difference.

@{fg shine}-What's not accepted-@{fg text}

'PUBLIC =240' 'public=500' 'PUBLIC= 250' 'PubLic=250' 'PUBLIC=-10' 'Quiet' 

@EndNode
///

/// "Requirements"
@Node "Require" "Requirements"

Minimal Requirements:
    
Amiga computer with 68020+ microprocessor and AmigaDOS 3.1

@EndNode
///
/// "Bugs"
@Node "bugs" "Known bugs"

- Wrong gadget colors by 16bit screen on Picasso96 and Voodoo. Solution: use PC screens.

- MUI programs becomes fragmented at different screens. Don't use GoScreen but the MUI
  utility "Public Screen Inspector" with comes with MUI.

- Altough, i use graphics libraries CloseFont(textFont)(a1) to close the used font. When
  i look by fonts in Scout, the font is listed, weird. I think is harmless, stays in memory
  tough.

@EndNode
///
/// "Tips"
@Node "tips" "Tips"

Look in the Presets drawer for some interesting configurated GoScreen icons for use with
AmigaWriter, StormC and DeluxeMusic 2.0.

@EndNode
///
/// "Technical"
@Node "tech" "Technical"

GoScreen gives message "can't open screen" when the screen can not be opened.
GoScreen gives message "can't open font" when the font can not be opened.

@EndNode
///
/// "Compilation"
@Node "Compilation" "Compilation of GoScreen"
    
GoScreen is assembled with BarFly 2.21 (05-Mai-03) full optimizations !
I think BarFly is the most powerful 68K assembler arround.
and runs of AmigaDOS 3.1

StormC4 is used for debugging.

Aminet software used:

ASM-One_V1.49 -the only assembler i've found that can bug-tracing at a 68060.
MCalc -programmers suitable calculator.
SnoopDOS 3.8 -shows much system calls, good for analyzing programs.
RKM2_ASM.lha - holds lots of example assembler sources for modern AmigaOS 3.1

My Amiga configuration:

 Amiga1200T 68060 59Mhz, 603e 200Mhz, ROM 3.1, OS3.9 BB2, RAM 128Mb, SCSI HD 8Gb,
 IDE DVD 16x40x, SCSI CD-R 6x4x, PARALLELZIP 100Mb, FlickerFixer/Scandoubler,
 Mediator Voodoo5 graphics with picasso96

 Processor board is BlizzardPPC with SCSI2 (Overclocked the 68060 to 59Mhz)

@EndNode
